  	<title>What Is Magnetism?</title>
	<exercises>
		<title>Warm-up Activities</title>
		<exercise>
			<p>Write down something you know about magnets or magnetism, and how you know it. Where do you use magnets in every day life?</p>
		</exercise>
	</exercises>
		
		
    <video youtube="qMJK_sjdUCw"><description>DESCRIPTION</description></video>
	
	<p>Magnets interact in lots of interesting ways with different types of materials. We will discuss mainly permanent magnets and ferromagnetic objects.</p>
	
	<definition>
		<title>Permanent magnets</title>
		<statement>
			<p><term>Permanent magnets</term> are objects that have both attractive and repulsive interactions with each other. These objects have a ``north" and a ``south" pole that react to each other in different ways. Like poles repel and opposite poles attract.</p>
		</statement>
	</definition>

	<definition>
		<title>Ferromagnetic magnets</title>
		<statement>
			<p><term>Ferromagnetic</term> materials (like iron, cobalt, and nickel) tend to be attracted to permanent magnets.</p>
		</statement>
	</definition>

